    "highlighting the differences in their performance and emphasizing the importance of selecting the right materials to achieve specific concrete characteristics.1.",
    "(SF) and (MK) enhance workability and flow at lower replacement levels; however, higher doses may reduce workability due to increased water demand.",
    "(FA) improves workability and extends setting time, particularly at lower replacement levels, due to a reduction in hydration heat.",
    "Conversely, materials such as (GGBFS), (RHA), (POFA), (SCBA), (SF) 15,000 High fineness of SF enhances compressive strength and durability due to its high pozzolanic reactivity and excellent pore-filling ability [125] (FA) 200-600 Moderate fineness improves long-term compressive strength and chloride resistance by providing secondary hydration and filling large pores over time [126] (GGBFS) 400-600 Fineness enables gradual strength development, making GGBFS effective in improving durability in chloride-rich environments [127] (MK) 10,000-15,000 High fineness improves early strength, reduces permeability, and contributes to a denser matrix due to rapid pozzolanic activity [128] Zeolite 2000-5000 Moderate fineness refines pore structure, enhancing durability through improved resistance to chemical attack while providing moderate strength [129] (RHA) 10,000-12,000 High fineness improves compressive strength and reduces water absorption, making RHA effective for long-term durability due to its fine pore-filling effect [130] (ESP) 200-400 Low fineness mainly acts as a filler, stabilizing the matrix but contributing little to strength or refined pore structure (WGP) 300-500 Moderate fineness improves packing density, reduces porosity, and enhances durability with minimal strength gains [131] (POFA) 300-400 Acts as a filler with modest improvements in durability; enhances stability in the matrix but contributes minimally to strength gain [106] (SCBA) 400-600 Moderate fineness allows SCBA to fill larger pores, slightly improving strength and durability by reducing water penetration ReviewVol.",
    ":(0123456789)Discover Civil Engineering (2024) 1:145 | https://doi.org/10.1007/s44290-024-00154-z Review and zeolite generally decrease workability when used at higher levels."
